    <title>First-Stage Sampling in Ranking and Selection: Beyond Variance Estimation</title>
    <updated>2025-01-29T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Weiwei Fan, Xuewen Li, Jun Luo, Shing Chih Tsai</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Operations Research&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This study sheds light on a crucial aspect of ranking-and-selection (R&amp;S) procedures—how the first-stage sample size, [Formula: see text], impacts the procedure efficiency beyond the variance estimation. This research demonstrates that the presence of [Formula: see text] helps reduce the probability of incorrect selection (PICS). However, this issue of [Formula: see text] has been traditionally ignored, thereby leading to unnecessarily conservativeness of existing R&amp;S procedures. To address this issue, the authors provide exact formulas for both indifference-zone (IZ) and IZ-free procedures, highlighting how [Formula: see text] influences PICS under worst-case configurations. Based on these formulas, this research further offers new guidelines on the choice of [Formula: see text] for the existing procedures and introduces an improved version of the classic IZ-free procedure. This research provides important insights for further enhancing the efficiency of R&amp;S in various potential applications.</content>
